THE RISK:
{
 "id": "grid-queue-construction-pause",
 "title": "Frankfurt's 24–36-month grid queue and Amsterdam's 350 MVA cap turn the venture's 12-month window into a delivery trough",
 "narrative": "78% of the modeled TAM sits in Germany and the Netherlands — precisely the two geographies where capacity additions are grid-gated. Frankfurt (60–75% of German capacity) faces 24–36-month grid-connection waits; Amsterdam is at 852 MW with a draft zoning plan capping new connections at 350 MVA until 2030; EMEA-wide, capacity under construction has plateaued at ~2.5 GW despite a 15 GW pipeline. PDU orders land at fit-out milestones, which are gated by energization dates, not by the 9% trend CAGR. If 2026 energizations slip right — and the queue data says many will — Year-1 orders slip with them, regardless of what the market does by 2030.",
 "category": "exogenous",
 "targetNodes": [
  "obtainableFactor"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "Frankfurt carries ~745 MW of IT load with grid connections facing 24–36-month waits; Amsterdam's draft umbrella zoning plan caps new connection capacity at 350 MVA until 2030; EMEA under-construction capacity has plateaued at ~2.5 GW on power and permitting constraints",
   "refs": [
    "digest:geo-DE#c20",
    "digest:geo-NL#c8",
    "digest:geo-NL#c3"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "Germany (0.50) and the Netherlands (0.28) are 78% of the geographic weight, and Frankfurt alone is 60–75% of the German base — so a grid-driven slip in these two hubs is a slip in most of the venture's addressable fit-out calendar",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:geo.DE",
    "ledger:geo.NL",
    "digest:geo-DE#c1",
    "digest:geo-DE#c4"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "The 9% CAGR is a 2030 trend, not a 2026 delivery schedule; YAM is a first-12-months number, so the slip compiles to obtainableFactor (pace), not to the trend node — Year-1 orderable fit-outs shrink even while the long-run TAM is intact",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:shape.cagr",
    "ledger:obtainableFactor",
    "profile:Stage"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "Grid congestion is a known headline, so it appears priced in — but the model prices it nowhere: shape.cagr is a smooth 9% and obtainableFactor is a generic benchmark. The surface appearance of 'strong secular demand' hides that demand in the window is lumpy and gated: pre-let capacity absorbed faster than it can be replaced means orders bunch AFTER energizations, which are exactly what is slipping.",
 "expectedObviousness": "medium",
 "falsifier": "H1-2026 evidence that Frankfurt and Amsterdam energizations are converting on schedule — e.g., JLL/C&W showing under-construction MW moving to live at or above the prior year's conversion rate in both hubs.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.45,
  "rationale": "Queue lengths and the 2.5 GW construction plateau are documented in current reporting; offsetting this, some 2026 deliveries already hold secured connections (e.g., Pure DC's 100 MVA private substation in Amsterdam), so a partial rather than total slip is the modal outcome. [evidence revision: Constraint premises are more strongly and consistently corroborated than the base hypothesis assumed (Statista lead times far exceed the 24-36 month figure cited; Mainova says mid-2030s), tightening the delivery-trough logic. However, ongoing conversions (AMS11 27MW opened Nov 2025, FRA18 launch, new Amsterdam permit) confirm partial-slip rather than total-stall remains modal, so a modest upward adjustment to 0.45 is warranted without overstating a full Year-1 collapse.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.4
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "obtainableFactor",
   "op": "scale",
   "value": 0.5,
   "note": "Roughly half of window-period fit-out milestones in DE/NL slip beyond the 12-month YAM horizon"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "Grid-connection queue length and new-connection moratoria in the Frankfurt region",
   "where": "TenneT/Amprion grid development and connection-request disclosures; Hessen regional planning dockets",
   "threshold": "Queue quotes lengthening beyond 36 months or a formal connection pause",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Under-construction → live conversion rate in Amsterdam and Frankfurt",
   "where": "JLL German data center market updates; Cushman & Wakefield EMEA data centre update (H1 2026)",
   "threshold": "Live-capacity additions <15% YoY in either hub",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "Finalization of Amsterdam's umbrella zoning plan connection cap",
   "where": "Gemeente Amsterdam zoning consultation docket; DC Byte Amsterdam market page",
   "threshold": "350 MVA cap adopted as drafted",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Build a named-project delivery calendar for the 2026–27 DE/NL fit-out pipeline (project, MW, energization date, GC/electrical contractor) and re-derive Year-1 obtainable from it",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "obtainableFactor",
   "note": "Replaces the generic 1–5% band with an energization-gated pipeline model"
  },
  {
   "action": "Add a second sales beachhead in a non-grid-gated CE market (Warsaw, Vienna) to hedge the DE/NL delivery trough",
   "type": "operational",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": "Poland's additions are growing fastest and are not FLAP-D-queue-bound"
  },
  {
   "action": "Offer stock-and-ship replacement SKUs with short lead times to capture demand that decouples from new-build energization",
   "type": "strategic",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": "Replacement demand in live halls is the segment least exposed to grid gates"
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "corroborated",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "Cushman & Wakefield: European data centre growth is shifting",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Cushman & Wakefield",
   "date": "2026-04-28",
   "excerpt": "Amsterdam, with 852 MW of operational capacity, has less room for further expansion... Capacity currently under construction has plateaued at around 2.5 GW. Across Europe, the explanation is often the same: power shortages, limited grid connections and lengthy permitting",
   "url": "https://www.cushmanwakefield.com/en/netherlands/news/2026/04/emea-datacentre-update-h2-2025",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Data center grid connection lead times by market 2025",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Statista",
   "date": "2026-01-06",
   "excerpt": "As of 2025, the average lead time for data centers to be connected to the power grid in both Amsterdam and Tokyo was 10 years, the longest of any major market. Frankfurt: 7 years.",
   "url": "https://www.statista.com/statistics/1651131/data-center-grid-connection-lead-times-by-market/",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Frankfurt at the Limit: Power Shortages Slow the Data Center Boom",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "igor'sLAB",
   "date": "2026-03-19",
   "excerpt": "The energy provider Mainova estimates that high-capacity new connections on a large scale will not be possible again until the mid-2030s.",
   "url": "https://www.igorslab.de/en/frankfurt-at-its-limit-power-shortages-are-slowing-the-boom-in-data-centers/",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
   "url": "https://www.statista.com/statistics/1651131/data-center-grid-connection-lead-times-by-market/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "As of 2025, the average lead time for data centers to be connected to the power grid in both Amsterdam and Tokyo was 10 years, the longest of any major market."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.igorslab.de/en/frankfurt-at-its-limit-power-shortages-are-slowing-the-boom-in-data-centers/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "The energy provider Mainova estimates that high-capacity new connections on a large scale will not be possible again until the mid-2030s."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://neospaces.de/en/insights/frankfurt-data-center-fra1-power-2026-q2",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Available power capacity is effectively zero, and new projects are migrating to the surrounding region."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.cushmanwakefield.com/en/netherlands/news/2026/04/emea-datacentre-update-h2-2025",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Amsterdam, with 852 MW of operational capacity, has less room for further expansion... Capacity currently under construction has plateaued at around 2.5 GW. Across Europe, the explanation is often the same: power shortages, limited grid connections and lengthy permitting"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.estatesgazette.co.uk/news/data-centre-vacancy-hits-record-low-as-demand-outstrips-supply/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "JLL said capacity is now being absorbed faster than it can be delivered, with around 83% of space currently under construction already pre-let"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.datacenterdynamics.com/en/news/digital-realty-opens-new-27mw-data-center-campus-in-amsterdam-the-netherlands/",
   "stance": "contradicts",
   "quote": "The facility, AMS11, has a capacity of 27MW of IT capacity across 12,000 sqm (129,165 sq ft), increasing the company's Dutch footprint to approximately 159MW."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://nltimes.nl/2026/07/07/construction-permit-granted-massive-data-center-amsterdam-zuidoost",
   "stance": "contradicts",
   "quote": "Construction permit granted for massive data center in Amsterdam Zuidoost"
  }
 ]
}

